				<font face="verdana" size="2" color="black">
				When I chose the name Steppenwolf, it was because I'd used it as an internet nick for 3 years and I identified with the character Harry Haller in the Hesse novel 'Steppenwolf.'  It didn't occur to me that the name violated the naming policy because it was copyrighted by a rock and roll band.  When, at level 16, a GM forced me to change it, I grumbled, but complied.  Now, I find there is a GM on Luclin where I play whose name is Lukkie Charmms, a copyrighted product trademark of General Mills.  My big heartache with the enforcement of the naming policy is not that it is oppressive so much as that it is entirely too subjective and arbitrary in its enforcement. GMs are allowed to break it at will but players are busted for the slightest infraction of it -- but not all players, just those who have been narced to the GMs.  Bah!  Verant, fix this NOW!  Your credibility is teetering in the balance.<BR>
<BR>
Steppy<BR>
Lvl 26 Bard<BR>
Luclin Server (home of GM Lukkie Charmms, blatantly in violation of Verant's own policies!)
